# How to Set Up Forta Attack Detector Alerts Using OpenZeppelin Defender

## Introduction
The Forta Attack Detector detects smart contract exploits early allowing you to respond quickly and prevent or mitigate an exploit targeting your protocol’s smart contracts. The OpenZeppelin Defender platform is a developer security platform that allows you to audit, deploy and monitor blockchain applications. Within Defender, you can easily and quickly begin utilizing the Attack Detector in order to protect your protocol’s smart contracts. Defender can take action of the Attack Detector’s alerts automatically pausing the protocol preventing loss of funds.

This doc will guide you through how to quickly and easily set up the Attack Detector within Defender and receive alerts as well as setting up automated actions. Please visit the [OpenZeppelin Defender docs here](https://docs.openzeppelin.com/defender) regarding any questions about how to use Defender.

## Initial Requirements
1. First log in to your OpenZeppelin Defender account and navigate to “Monitors” on the top. You will be prompted to create your first Monitor (previously known as Sentinels) if you have not done so already. Click on “Create Monitor”. 

    Monitors allow you to gain full visibility into your smart contracts' risks and behaviors. You can detect threats, get alerts on threats and anomalies, and automatically respond and resolve issues.

2. Monitor Templates help simplify the process of creating a Monitor. As seen in the screenshot, there are multiple template modules available to you based on the type of Monitors needed for your use case.  In this guide we will utilize the “Attack Detector Feed” template, highlighted below. 

    <img alt="" src="data:image/png;base64," />


## Configure Your Monitor
3. Once you click on the “Attack Detector Feed Monitor Template” you will see the “Monitor Summary” on the right hand side indicating the Forta Bot ID which belongs to the Attack Detector Feed. 

    <img alt="" src="data:image/png;base64," />

4. Give your Monitor a name and choose the smart contract in which you are interested in monitoring. Only alerts for contracts pertaining to your protocol should be consumed. Unless the contract addresses of your protocols are specified in the contracts field, the monitor will not trigger. If the contract is not available in the drop down, you must add it to your address book within Defender. Leaving this section empty will result in a firehose of all of the Attack Detector's alerts.

    <img alt="" src="data:image/png;base64," />

5. Following that is the "Transaction Filters" section, which allows for code to specify a custom filter, if specified, it will be called with a list of matches found for a given block. This allows the monitor to use other datasources and custom logic to evaluate whether a transaction matches. In the example below, you can find an example of a filter used to specify for metadata in the Attack Detector's findings. Please note that transaction filters are not required.

<img src='data:image/png;base64,'/>

```Javascript
exports.handler = async function (params) {
    const payload = params.request.body;
    const matches = [];
    const events = payload.events;

    for(const event of events) {
        matches.push({
            hash: event.alert.hash,
            metadata: {
                attackerAddress: event.alert.metadata.attackerAddress,
                findingType: event.alert.findingType
            }
        });
    }

    return { matches };
}
```

6. Next, navigate below to the “Alert Conditions” section and set the minimum severity to critical. 

    Additionally, you can select the minimum number of scan node confirmations as well as specify for specific Alert IDs. The type of Alert ID you would be interested in is dependent on your level or risk and false positives tolerance. Below, you will find the four (4) different Attack Detector Alert IDs. The Attack Detector monitors and alerts on various stages of the exploitation; funding, preparation, exploitation and money laundering. The Alert IDs below can be classified as ‘pre-exploitation’, ‘ongoing-exploitation’ and ‘post-exploitation’. For example, the ATTACK-DETECTOR-1 Alert ID will only fire post exploitation as it requires alerts from all  4 stages to be present. 

    If you aim to further minimize the risk of false positives and your goal is to utilize this solution to prevent an attack, then subscribing to the ATTACK-DETECTOR-PREPARATION alert is the correct Alert ID to filter on. If you have a higher tolerance for false positives and are open to pausing your protocol when an attack is in progress or shortly after that, then subscribing to all of the Attack Detector Alert IDs is recommended. The Attack Detector’s Alert IDs are: 

    | AlertID                       | Stage             |
    |-------------------------------|-------------------|
    | ATTACK-DETECTOR-1             | post-exploitation |
    | ATTACK-DETECTOR-2             | ongoing-exploitation |
    | ATTACK-DETECTOR-3             | ongoing-exploitation |
    | ATTACK-DETECTOR-PREPARATION   | pre-exploitation  |

    Go [here](https://app.forta.network/attack-detector/documentation) to learn more about the Attack Detector Alert IDs.

    <img alt="" src="data:image/png;base64," />

7. Within the “Alerts Conditions” section, Defender allows you to execute an action based on the type of the incoming threat detected by the Forta Attack Detector and the permissions available within your contract. 

    Actions allow you to implement custom app logic for on-chain and off-chain operations. You can enable automated responses to threats detected by the Monitor and Incident Response modules.

    ### Actions Use Cases: 
    - Automate smart contract operations
    - Execute actions as response to a Monitor alert
    - Automate Incident Response steps with Actions
    - Create transaction proposals from multisigs, relayers, and more
    - No-code (form-based) for transaction proposals
    - Call external APIs and interact with other smart contracts  
    __

    In this example, we will set up an emergency pause action for our contract. Go [here](https://docs.openzeppelin.com/defender/v2/module/actions) for more information.

    Additionally, here is where you can select which notification channel you would prefer to receive your incoming alert. If you do not have a notification channel already configured, you will be required to do that within the setting window. We will go over this in step 12.

    <img alt="" src="data:image/png;base64," />

## Creating an Action
8. In order to select an Action, you must have a certain Action created beforehand. If you do not have one, make sure you save the current Monitor you have been working on before heading over to the Actions window. Once your Monitor is saved, you can always go back to it and make any necessary changes.

    <img alt="" src="data:image/png;base64," />

    <img alt="" src="data:image/png;base64," />



9. Under the “Code” section you will be required to insert Javascript code that will execute when the conditions of your Actions are met. Go [here](https://docs.openzeppelin.com/defender/v2/tutorial/actions) for further instructions on how to create that. Here is an example for pausing the contract.

    <img alt="" src="data:image/png;base64," />


    ```javascript
    const { ethers } = require("ethers");
    const { DefenderRelaySigner } = require("@openzeppelin/defender-relay-client/lib/ethers")

    // Set up ABI
    const ABI = [
        // Add only the function signatures needed for pausing
        "function pause() public",
        "function unpause() public",
        "function paused() public view returns (bool)"
    ];

    // Function to pause the contract
    async function pauseContract(contract) {
    if (!(await contract.paused())) {
        console.log("Pausing contract...");
        const pauseTx = await contract.pause();
        await pauseTx.wait();
        console.log("Contract paused.");
    }else {
    console.log("Contract is already paused.");
    }
    }

    //Main Autotask handler
    exports.handler = async function(credentials) {
        const provider = new DefenderRelayProvider(credentials);
        const signer = new DefenderRelaySigner(credentials, provider, {speed: "fast"});
        const contract = new ethers.contract("0x123")

        await pauseContract(contract);
    };

    ```
10. Once saved, you can access all of your different actions from the Actions panel.

    <img alt="" src="data:image/png;base64," />


11. Now returning to creating our Monitor, under the ‘Alerts’ section we can find the Action that we just created. Let’s select that and click on “Save Monitor”. And you’re almost done.


    <img alt="" src="data:image/png;base64," />


## Set Up Alert Conditions
12. Lastly, here is where you can configure how and where you will be receiving any incoming alerts. If you have not already preconfigured your notifications channel, head over to “Manage” on the top right hand corner of your options menu and select “Notification Channels”. You cannot configure your notifications from within the monitor window. Make sure you have saved any changes you’ve made to your Monitor before leaving this page. You will still be required to go back and select your specific notification channel for the monitor under the ‘Alerts’ section.

    Here you can select from a variety of different ways you can receive any incoming alerts and notifications. In the example below you can see that any incoming notifications will be sent to my email. Defender allows you to seamlessly integrate with several different solutions such as Slack or Telegram. An indepth look at all Defender integrations can be found [here](https://docs.openzeppelin.com/defender/v2/integrations).
